sman-raul-ruiz-marries-monica-rivers/9304523/|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The Desert Sun|date=2014-05-19}}</ref>\n| religion     = [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]]<ref>[http://nationaljournal.com/thenextamerica/politics/calif-36th-house-district-raul-ruiz-d-20121106 The Next America], [[National Journal]], Updated: December 3, 2012.</ref>\n| website      = {{URL|http://ruiz.house.gov}}\n}}\n\n'''Raul Ruiz''' (born August 25, 1972) is an American medical doctor and politician. He is a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] and a member of the [[Democratic party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Nocera|first=Kate|title=Raul Ruiz win tells story of Election 2012|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1112/84020.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=Politico|date=2012-11-18}}</ref>  In what was considered a major upset,<ref>[http://www.pe.com/local-news/politics/ben-goad-headlines/20121106-congress-district-36-raul-ruiz-unseats-mary-bono-mack-in-upset.ece Raul Ruiz unseats Mary Bono Mack in upset] ''[[Riverside Press-Enterprise]]'', November 7, 2012. {{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref> Ruiz defeated [[gerrymandering|redistricted]], [[incumbent]] [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] representative [[Mary Bono Mack]] in the November 2012 general election in [[California's 36th congressional district]]. Ruiz was reelected to Congress in the 2014 elections, after what was considered one of the most competitive congressional races in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Freking|first=Kevin|title=Congressional freshmen face tough challenges|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/may/3/congressional-freshmen-face-tough-challenges/?page=all|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=Washington Times|date=2014-3-3}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRuiz was born on August 25, 1972<ref>{{cite web|last=Kondracke |first=Morton |url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/raul-ruiz-d-calif-36.html |title=Raul Ruiz, D (Calif.-36) |publisher=Roll Call |date=1972-08-25 |accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref> in Zacatecas, Mexico<ref>{{cite news|last=Honore|first=Marcel|title=A look into Raul Ruiz|url=http://www.desertsun.com/article/20121208/NEWS03/312090001|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The Desert Sun|date=12-9-2012}}</ref> and raised in [[Coachella, California]].<ref name=\"voxxi\">[http://www.voxxi.com/raul-ruiz-doctor/ Profile Raul Ruiz, first Hispanic to receive 3 degrees from Harvard]</ref> His parents were farmworkers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drraulruiz.com/about|publisher=Dr. Raul Ruiz for Congress|title=About|accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Coachella Valley High School]] at age 17, and went to [[UCLA]] in 1990, graduating [[magna cum laude]] before attending [[Harvard Medical School]].<ref name=voxxi/> He was the first Hispanic to receive three graduate degrees from [[Harvard University]]: an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] from the Harvard Medical School; an [[Master of Public Policy|M.P.P.]] from the [[Harvard Kennedy School of Government]]; and an [[Master of Public Health|M.P.H.]] from the [[Harvard School of Public Health]].<ref name=voxxi/>\n\nIn 1997, while attending Harvard as a medical student, Ruiz participated in an annual [[Thanksgiving]] protest in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts]]. Ruiz was one of 25 people arrested at the event. The charges were later dropped as part of a deal that also dismissed claims of police brutality.<ref name=\"desert\">{{cite news|last=McGinty|first=Kate|title=Mary Bono Mack and Raul Ruiz: A fact check on the congressional debate - |url=http://isun.blogs.mydesert.com/2012/10/12/mary-bono-mack-and-raul-ruiz-a-fact-check-on-the-congressional-debate/|accessdate=25 April 2014|newspaper=MyDesert.com|date=12 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nTwo years later, in 1999, Ruiz took part in another Thanksgiving protest at which he read a letter of support for [[Leonard Peltier]], who was convicted and sentenced to two consecutive terms of life imprisonment for first degree murder in the shooting of two [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) special agents during a 1975 conflict on the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]]. During the 2012 congressional campaign, the incident was used as an attack by his opponent, Mary Bono Mack. In response, Ruiz's campaign stated that he had not supported Peltier.<ref name=\"desert\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Clarke|first1=Chris|title=Coachella Valley Congress Race Turns Nasty|url=http://www.kcet.org/updaily/socal_focus/government/coachella-valley-congress-race-turns-nasty.html|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=KCET|date=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Medical career==\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard University]], Ruiz spent time working abroad in [[Mexico]], [[El Salvador]], and [[Serbia]], before taking a job as an emergency physician at the [[Eisenhower Medical Center]], a nonprofit hospital in the Coachella Valley. He founded the Coachella Valley Healthcare Initiative in 2010. In 2011, he became senior associate dean at the School of Medicine at [[University of California, Riverside]].<ref name=voxxi/><ref name=\"wt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/raul-ruiz-62342/|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=7 November 2012|title=Raul Ruiz}} {{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he received a [[Commander's Award for Public Service]] from the U.S. Army's [[82nd Airborne Division]] for his humanitarian efforts for victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref name=voxxi/> Ruiz's background as a physician has gained him attention for several incidents in which he has provided medical aid to fellow airline passengers, including conservative columnist [[Lisa De Pasquale]].<ref>http://dailycaller.com/2014/07/18/dem-lawmaker-rushes-to-save-conservative-journo-during-seizure/</ref> \n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n;2012\nRuiz ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 2012 as a first-time candidate in {{ushr|CA|36}}. The district had previously been the 45th, represented by 15-year incumbent [[Mary Bono|Mary Bono Mack]].  While Ruiz was initially regarded as a long shot to win,<ref name=Clinton/> he gained traction in the polls in the months before the November election.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}} He was endorsed by [[Bill Clinton]] in October 2012.<ref name=Clinton>{{cite news|last1=Terlecky|first1=Megan|title=Fmr Pres. Clinton Endorses Ruiz for Congress|url=http://www.kesq.com/news/-Fmr-Pres-Clinton-Endorses-Ruiz-for-Congress/17108768|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=KESQ|date=23 October 2012}}</ref> He was elected with 52.9% of the vote, to Bono Mack's 47.1%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. Raul Ruiz (D-Calif.)|url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/45281.html|website=Roll Call|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref> Upon taking office in January 2013, Ruiz became the first Democrat to represent the Coachella Valley since [[John V. Tunney]] was elected, in 1971.<ref name=\"tunney\">{{cite news|first=Jason A.|last=Bezis|url=http://calpolitical.blogspot.com/2012/11/riverside-county-for-obama-in-2012.html|title=CalPolitiCal: Riverside County - For Obama in 2012, First Democrat Ever to Win Twice}}</ref>{{Better source|date=August 2014}}\n\n;2014\nRuiz ran for re-election in 2014. He competed in the blanket primary on June 3, 2014, finishing first with 50.3% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Vote|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2014-primary/pdf/2014-complete-sov.pdf|website=Secretary of State's Office|publisher=State of California|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=Primary Results: California House Races (Updated)|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/california-primary-results-2014/|accessdate=19 August 2014|publisher=Roll Call|date=4 June 2014}}</ref> Ruiz then faced Republican nominee and state assemblyman [[Brian Nestande]] in the general election, which took place November 4, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Blumenthal|first=Paul|title=Vulnerable House Incumbents Raising Big Money For 2014 Races|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/16/2014-election-house-incumbents_n_3604746.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=2013-07-16}}</ref> Despite being considered one of the most vulnerable incumbent members of the House of Representatives, Ruiz was re-elected with 54.2% of the vote, to Nestande's 45.8%.\n\n===Tenure===\nIn April 2013, Ruiz introduced his first bill, the SelectUSA Authorization Act of 2013. The bill would incentivize international corporations to invest in creating manufacturing jobs in the United States rather than overseas.<ref>http://www.kesq.com/news/Rep-Raul-Ruiz-introduces-his-first-bill-in-Washington/19682182</ref> The bill has not been voted on by the House.<ref>{{cite web|title=H.R.1413: SelectUSA Authorization Act of 2013|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/bills/113/hr1413|website=New York Times|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> \n\nIn April 2013, Ruiz voted for [[CISPA]], which would allow for the sharing of Internet traffic information between the U.S. government and technology and manufacturing companies.<ref>{{cite web|title=H R 624|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/113/house/1/votes/117/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Ruiz voted against repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://thehill.com/blogs/healthwatch/politics-elections/304727-nrcc-hits-calif-dems-over-obamacare-rates | title=NRCC hits Calif. Dems over ObamaCare rates | author=Sam Baker | date=11 June 2013 | accessdate=4 November 2013 | publisher=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll154.xml | title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 154 | accessdate=4 November 2013 | publisher=House.gov}}</ref> \nDuring his 2012 campaign for Congress, Ruiz stated his support for the [[Affordable Care Act]]. As full implementation of the law began in late 2013, its popularity with the public plummeted as many Americans had their policies canceled due to lacking coverage requirements mandated by the law,<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2013/11/07/politics/obama-obamacare-apology/ Obama apologizes for insurance cancellations due to Obamacare - CNN.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the federal health care online exchange had many technical problems that delayed the ability to sign up to new plans.<ref>[http://www.forbes.com/sites/lorenthompson/2013/12/03/healthcare-gov-diagnosis-the-government-broke-every-rule-of-project-management/ HealthCare.gov Diagnosis: The Government Broke Every Rule Of Project Management - Forbes<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nRuiz voted against the Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act, which would ban abortions that take place 20 or more weeks after fertilization.<ref>{{cite web|title=House Vote 251 - Approves New Abortion Restrictions|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/113/house/1/251|website=New York Times|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, a family emergency prevented Ruiz from casting votes on two immigration bills.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Felci|first1=Erica|title=Raul Ruiz not elaborating on missed immigration vote|url=http://www.desertsun.com/story/news/politics/2014/08/05/rep-ruiz-elaborating-missed-immigration-vote/13611197/|accessdate=10 September 2014|publisher=Desert Sun|date=8-5-2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs|Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs]]\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|Committee on Veterans' Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs|Subcommittee on Disability Assistance and Memorial Affairs]]\n**[[United States House Veterans' Affairs Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n\n==Personal==\nRuiz married Monica Rivers in 2014.<ref name=wedding/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Physicians in US Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ruiz.house.gov/ Congressman Raul Ruiz] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.drraulruiz.com/ Raul Ruiz for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Raul_Ruiz_%5BD-36%5D|Raul Ruiz}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = R000599 | ballot = Raul_Ruiz | nndb = | votesmart = 136407 | govtrack = 412519 | opencong = 412519 | rollcall = 45281 | politifact = | fec = H2CA36439 | opensecrets = N00033510 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney =  | ontheissues = CA/Raul_Ruiz.htm | congress = raul-ruiz/2109 | worldcat = | c-span = raulruiz02 | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = e540f502-4bbc-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=California|\n  district=36 |\n  before=[[Janice Hahn]] |\n  start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Keith Rothfus]]<br><small>R-[[Pennsylvania]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=411th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brad Schneider]]<br><small>D-[[Illinois]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{CA-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata\n| NAME              = Ruiz, Raul\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = \n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =   25 August 1972\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =  Zacatecas, Mexico\n| DATE OF DEATH     = \n| PLACE OF DEATH    = \n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruiz, Raul}}\n[[Category:American politicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American Seventh-day Adventists]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Harvard Univers